snippet.textDisplay: This has been undoubtedly one of the most joyous, melodious and rhythmic example of classic Punjabi folk that I've heard in a while...and it was great to see the Gurdas Maan that I grew up listening to on Delhi Doordarshan in the 1980s still in full flow, as well as the undeniable upcoming talent of Diljit Dosanjh. The 2nd half of the song that dwelt on the sadness of partition was very moving. That being said, I did have some serious issues with the 1st half of the song. The longing for the 'good old days' bit was mildly annoying. What was more than annoying and rather disturbing was yet another case of attempting to control the female body and mind. The specific mention of 'embroidered dresses', 'disappearing earrings' and alas, no more 'traditional veils' is so clearly gender-specific. Also, as we all know too damn well, that when 'men date women without the intention to marry them' then which side attracts most of the outrage. HINT: It's rarely the male!
